# Lessons Learned

## **OpenLineage Naming Conventions**

It is critical that tools/lineage emitters adhere to the Openlineage naming convention, in particular relating to datasets. This is because datasets are the key links that tie lineage chains together (job \-\> dataset \-\> job), and so ensuring that dataset readers and writers are using the same dataset namespace/name is key.

The convention is: *A dataset, or table, is organized according to a producer, namespace, database and (optionally) schema.*

E.g.

| Namespace | Name |
| ----- | ----- |
| oracle://{host}:{port} | {serviceName}.{schema}.{table} or {sid}.{schema}.{table} |
| postgres://{host}:{port} | {database}.{schema}.{table} |
| file | {path} |
| s3://{bucket name} | {object key} |

A more extensive list is here: [https://openlineage.io/docs/spec/naming/](https://openlineage.io/docs/spec/naming/)

Exceptions:

Feast is somewhat of an exception to this rule, given that it provides a logical data layer that sits on top of the physical data storage layer. Instead Feast uses:

|  | Namespace | Name |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Apply** | **Feast Registry (per convention)** *postgres://postgres:5432* | **Feast Registry (per convention)** *warehouse.customer\_features\_view*  |
| **Materialiaze** | **Feast Project Name *lineage*** | **Online\_store\_{view\_name} *online\_store\_customer\_features\_view*** |

## **Integration Approaches**

At this point we see a number of options in terms of open lineage integration approach. It may be desirable to cover a number of these.

### Native tool integration

This has been the default approach thus far, characterised by creating OL integrations on a tool by tool basis. While this is the preferred approach in terms of capturing the specific nuances of each tool's lineage events, via custom built integrations and data mappings, it is also the most labour intensive and difficult to ensure consistency. For instance ensuring all integrations adhere to the naming convention is critical, as well as ensuring the level of lineage event meta-data/facets are what we want.

### Auto-Instrumentation

Following similar approaches used in X like Opentelemetry, there is a possibility of attempting to allow lineage events we captured automatically. OTel ‘monkey patches’ well-known libraries for specific tasks (e.g. HTTP or SQL Clients), intercepting specific function calls and triggering logging events. We could follow a similar approach with OpenLineage subject to further investigation, with the obvious downside of a maintenance overhead in maintaining version compatibility with these libraries.

### SDK

The most basic, and powerful approach to capture lineage is simply to use an OpenLineage SDK. A basic python SDK already exists for OpenLineage, and we could explore augmenting this to make event generation even more streamlined. However this obviously comes with the significant drawback for requiring manual user coding. Nonetheless it should be part of the overall solution as a fall-back mechanism.

### Pull

Other approaches/standards in the same space (e.g. OpenDataDiscovery) take a pull-based approach, where they provide a generic adapter framework that can pull lineage data from specific APIs and convert it to their own standard format. Currently they have adapters for MLFlow and KFP, however this is an anti-pattern as they effectively poll APIs at fixed internals, and also carries the disadvantage of data not being captured real-time. 

